<h2>HVAC Systems in Mississippi</h2>

<h3>Climate Considerations</h3>
<p>Mississippi's subtropical climate presents unique challenges and opportunities for HVAC system design and operation. The state experiences long, hot, humid summers with average temperatures regularly exceeding 90¬∞F and heat index values often surpassing 105¬∞F. High humidity levels, frequently above 70% relative humidity, place additional strain on air conditioning systems, as they must work harder to remove moisture from the air while maintaining comfortable indoor temperatures. This climate pattern results in cooling seasons that typically extend from April through October, with peak demand occurring during July and August when systems may operate continuously for weeks at a time.</p>

<p>Winter heating requirements in Mississippi are generally moderate, with average low temperatures rarely dropping below 30¬∞F except in the northern regions of the state. However, the high humidity levels can make winter temperatures feel colder than they actually are, and homes still require reliable heating systems for comfort during December through February. The state's climate favors heat pump installations, which can provide efficient heating and cooling year-round, though backup resistance heating is recommended for the occasional extreme cold snaps that can occur.</p>

<p>Indoor air quality considerations are particularly important in Mississippi due to high outdoor humidity levels and the prevalence of mold and allergens. HVAC systems must be properly sized and equipped with adequate dehumidification capabilities to maintain indoor humidity levels between 40-60% for optimal comfort and health. Additionally, the long operating seasons mean that equipment reliability and energy efficiency are critical factors, as system failures during peak summer months can be both uncomfortable and expensive to address on an emergency basis.</p>

